{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2853b9b8-1a62-41c5-8a1a-22fd362dd95c","content":"## Connecting MCP Inspector to a C# stdio Server\n\n**1. Install & launch the Inspector:**\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector\n```\nThis opens a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`).\n\n**2. Configure the connection:**\n- **Transport Type:** `STDIO`\n- **Command:** `dotnet`\n- **Arguments:** `run --project /path/to/YourServer.csproj`\n\n   *(Or point to a built DLL: command `dotnet`, args `/path/to/YourServer.dll`)*\n\n**3. Click \"Connect\"** — the Inspector spawns your process and communicates over stdin/stdout.\n\n**4. Debug in the UI:**\n- **Tools tab** — lists discovered tools; click one to send a test call and inspect the JSON response.\n- **Resources / Prompts tabs** — test other MCP capabilities.\n- **Notifications pane** — shows server logs and protocol-level messages.\n\n**Key tips:**\n- Make sure your server writes MCP JSON-RPC to **stdout** only. Route any diagnostic logging to **stderr** — anything else on stdout will break the protocol.\n- If you need to attach a debugger, launch the server separately with `dotnet run` and use `--transport sse` (if supported), or set a startup delay so you can attach to the process.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"aad76dca-6ff4-4ecb-bc77-cfcd11110857","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to search a codebase for this. Let me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":397,"requestId":"5C35:1C6615:1CD21CD:1FEF31F:69FA9335"},"id":"954679e8-ab5e-49d3-a12f-7a1d04508809","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:02:58.877Z","parentId":"b6444ee3-6973-4995-8d87-eb107972fd9b"}
